Content:
The example given -- evaluating a new hash mapping the keys x, y, and z to random numbers in the range [0:100) -- is expressible in python3 as:<p><pre><code>  {(x, random.randrange(100)) for x in ["x", "y", "z"]}
</code></pre>
My point wasn't that "tap" is identical in functionality, it was actually the opposite: for the use cases here, both "tap" and "returning" are inferior to the python syntax.<p>That said, I continue to assert that this is a dumb example and you should just initialize the empty hash like your parents did.
